Repetition: Loops 
Loops give us major problem solving power.  Without them programs would be useful for solving only small problems, like we have been doing.  Loops allow us to write a finite number of statements but to have them executed many many (possibly infinite) times, by repeating at run-time rather than at write-time.  
A "for loop" is designed to be used when we know we need to repeat a block of statements a specific number of times.  We call this definite looping; we know when we write the code how many times to repeat.
We designate the code block to repeat, and we specify a variable to count the repetitions (called the loop index); we give that variable a starting value (often 0); we write a boolean comparison expression to answer the question "do we repeat again?", and we write an expression telling how to change the value of the index at the end of each repetition (often increment by 1).
To complete this problem, type in this JavaScript program (in proper myMain format):

5408c8203f84d4d07b6d0962.text:
Write a program that will print out the sum of the integers from 1 to 99, including 1 and 99.  
We will use a for loop to do this.
You will also need an "accumulator", a variable that has its value bumped up each time you go through the loop body.
Since we are summing, the accumulator will be initialized to 0 (the additive identity) outside the loop.  With a counter, the variable is bumped by some
fixed amount (often 1).  With an accumulator, the variable is bumped up by perhaps different amounts each time it is increased.
Think of an accumulator as a bucket.  We will accumulate a final value by adding into the bucket parts of the final amount, many times.
Lesson here: the loop index is a variable that can be used inside the loop body; it is often used to generate a sequence of numbers, or to count how many times the loop body has run.
Style: Use one for loop and no other loops.

We can start the accumulator at 2 (2^1).  After printing the value in the accumulator in the loop body, we double the value stored in

Doing the problem this way, the loop has to end when it goes past 2^10.
By the way, 2^10 is 1024.  This is the value we means in "computer speak" when we say 1K.  The K means roughly 1000,
but really is 2 to the 10th power.  We do everything in binary (base 2).

541646a76ba011bd0533f7c0.text:
Repetition: While Loops 
A second type of loop statement in JavaScript is the while loop.  
A while loop is less rigidly structured than a for loop; 
in a while loop we have to manually set up and maintain any loop index variables, counters, etc. we might need as part of the code in the loop body.
We use while loops primarily for what we call indefinite looping, where we do
not know (when we write the code) how many times the loop body will need to execute.  
It should be noted that these loop forms (for, while) are notational conveniences.  We use for loops primarily for definite looping,
and we use while loops primarily for indefinite looping; the syntax of each is set up to help create these patterns easily.  
However, computationally they are equivalent in their capabilities.
Anything we can do with a for loop, we can do with a while loop as well, and vice versa.
This means we can do definite loops with while ( but a for loop would be more convenient ). We can also do indefinite looping with a for loop (but
a while would be easier).  It is a bit more common to use a while loop for definite looping than it is to use a for loop for indefinite.
We will see this in the problems in this folder.
As with for loops we will write a boolean comparison expression to answer the question "should we execute the loop body another time?" ; this expression will usually examine the variables being used in the loop body.
To complete this problem, type in this JavaScript program (remember to use the myMain function format for style points):
  var x = 1; // loop index varible
  while ( x This is a definite loop; it is set up to execute the loop body 5 times. Note that the loop index variable (x) we had to set up and 
increment ourselves.  We started x at 1, and stopped when it became larger than 5. In a for loop, this bookkeeping is done automatically for us.
For this while loop, we print the square of the index variable each time we execute the loop body.  Thus, the output is a sequence of 
the squares of the first 5 positive integers.

Scope 
"Scope" is the term we use for the parts of a program in which a particular declared variable is visible (useable).  "Scope rules" are the decision procedures 
that allow us to determine what storage location in memory is denoted when we see a variable name in our code.  
In other words, when you see a variable used in an expression,  you can decide which "var" declaration is being used. 
It is possible, for example, to have several lines that look like "var x ;" in your code.   
When we see something like  "x = 5 ;" we need to know which of the several "var x ;" lines is the variable being referenced in the expression.
In JavaScript we have two main scopes: global, and local. 
Global scope is the collection of variables and names (function names) declared outside of all function definitions.
We can have code statements at the global level, and
we can have variable declarations at the global level. A global variable can be seen and used inside any function, as well
as in code at the global level.
Local scope is the collection of variables and names declared inside a function definition (this includes the parameters).
A local variable can be seen and used by any code that is inside the function it is declared in, but it is invisible (undefined) 
in code that is global, or inside other function declarations.
We are not going to use global code in most of our programs.  For these in this section, where we are specifically learning about
global vs. local, we will write and use some.
To complete this overview, type in and run this program:
"use strict"; 

var gx = 5; // global var declaration

function myMain() {
  alert( gx ); // use of global var from inside local function scope
}

alert(gx);  // use of global var from global scope
myMain();
Here the variable "gx" is in the global scope (we say "gx is a global variable") because it is declared not inside any function.
Since it is global, we can use it inside any function.  Hence, we can print our its value from inside of myMain.  We can also print its value
at the global level.  
Note also that the name "myMain" is also a global name; this is why the call to myMain is outside any function as well.
That call is a global code statement.  For most of our programs, that is the only global executable statement we will have.
In this code, we have two global executable statements: the alert, and then the call to myMain.

Write a program that will generate a single random number between 0 and 50 (but never quite being 50) and print it. 
Math.random produces numbers in the range [0,1).  Here we need numbers in an expanded range [0,50), with the lower end still 
at 0. We want the distribution to remain uniform.  So to do this, we can simply generate a random number and multiply
it by a factor that will expand the range upward.  The obvious factor (in this case) is 50.  All numbers generated 
by Math.random are then used as a percentage, telling how far into the range [0,50) to go to get the
final random output.
Let's reason about the range that results after this scaling.  Since Math.random might generate a 0, and since 0*50 is zero, the scaling might also generate 0 (as we wish).  Since Math.random with almost (but not quite) generate a 1, the scaling will generate (almost 1)*50, or almost but not quite 50 (as we wish).
One last comment... mathematically, we are talking about numbers with precision after the decimal point here (floating point, or real number values).  We are not trying to generate random integers in this program.  We will do that in later programs.

This problem illustrates two new capabilities: generating random integers, and moving the lower range up from 0. 
For integers, we will use Math.floor to take a random real number and make it integer. Note the twist here... the integer range is [0,100], meaning we want to include the upper end (100). Since Math.random will never generate exactly 1, if we scale the range by multiplying by 100, we will never quite get 100 and then Math.floor will back that down to the integer 99. So if we want 100 as possible output, we must scale to (almost) 101 and let Math.floor truncate to 100.
For the second output, we note that we need to shift the range up 5 from 0. The high end of the range we want is 25, so if we generate a number between 0 and 20, then add 5 we get a range of 5 to 25. So we can scale the range by multiplying the output of Math.random, and we can shift the range by adding to the result of Math.random (or the result of Math.floor(scaled random).

Write a program that creates a function value that is not bound to a name, and then bind that anonymous function value to a global name. 
A function value with no name bound to it is called "anonymous".  An anonymous function can still be defined and later bound to a name (saved for later execution).
In this problem we illustrate function as first class values by creating a function with no name (an anonymous function)
and then "binding" that function value to a name with "=" assignment.
To create an anonymous function value, we use the "function" keyword as we are accustomed to doing, but we do not put a name
after the keyword.  We do create an argument list (in parentheses) and the code body (in curly braces).
It is identical to defining a named function except we do not give it a name.
Here is an example (using the code from the previously defined named function "double"):
function ( n ) {  return 2*n; }
Again, this is a function value... it is the same thing for type "function" as writing the number value "5" is for type "number".
It is valid JavaScript, and we must now decide what we wish to do with this value.  In this program we will take that
function value, and bind it to a global name using assignment.  In the next program, we will see how to execute that
function value without ever naming it.
Details. First at the global level create an anonymous function value using the previous code for "double" with one argument (as shown
in the previous pre-format box).  Assign that anonymous function to the global variable "double" using assignment.
Then define the global function (myMain) as we usually do.  Inside myMain, call double(5) and print the returned result.
Notes. This program illustrates that the "normal" way of defining functions -- using the "function" keyword and a name for the function --
is actually a shorthand notation for doing what we are doing here... creating a nameless function value, and then binding it to a global name.
Binding it to a global name is what makes us able to run the function from within our other functions.
Also, we must be careful to get our code in the right order.  Since we are explicitly creating a global variable (the name for the function) we
must do that declaration and binding before we call myMain.  If we do not, when myMain runs and tried to call the function bound to 
the name "double", that global variable will not yet have been declared.  So do things in this order: 
 declare the global variable "double" and assign a function to it   declare function myMain , that calls "double" call myMain to kick it all off Relevance to objects.We will be (in the next module) putting functions inside objects (we call them "methods" for historical reasons).

DataData is the basic information we use computers to manipulate for us.  People and place names, ages, heights, lengths, dollars and cents, time, sentences, all these are information we may wish to have a computer program use.  JavaScript provides 3 types of fundamental (basic, simple) data:     number
    string (or text)
    boolean
Numbers are formed from digits 0-9, the negative symbol (-) and perhaps a decimal point (.) .
Examples include 11, -3.2, 27.12398745, 9.0, -10000, .25, 0.25
Strings are sequences of alphabetic characters, digits, and punctuation characters enclosed in quote marks.  
Examples include "hello", "COMP 110", "Welcome to class!", "x", "100", "up/down and side-ways"
Boolean data represent logical truth; there are only two boolean values: true and false .
We do not put quotes around true and false, we just use them as special words.  The value true is boolean, but the value "true" is a string. In similar fashion,
the value 200 is a number, but the value "200" is a string.
We will look at boolean in detail later.  In this module, we will practice mostly with numbers and strings.
OutputIn order for a computer program to be useful to us, it not only has to manipulate information, if must get that information out to us in a form we can understand and use.  This is called output.  Programming languages usually offer many ways to get a computer to output information. For JavaScript we will start with the very basic "print something to the screen" function.  This is the alert function.
The alert function in JavaScript produces a popup box on the screen, with the requested output printed inside the box.
Using the alert function it is our first example of a function call.   
When we call a function we are asking that the program perform the named activity, and we pass information to the function to use 
during its activity.  To call a function (in this case, the "alert" function) we write its name and in parentheses we write the information we wish to pass in (called parameters, or arguments). 
So let's try calling the alert function to get some output.
To complete this problem, type the following JavaScript line, run it, and then submit it for credit:
&nbsp&nbsp&nbsp alert( "data types: number, string, boolean" ) ;Make sure you pay careful attention to where all the blank characters are inside the quotes, and how many there are.  To get this program correct, your quoted string will have to be exactly the same as the one shown there.  This sort of detail is very important in programming and it can be very frustrating to you -- the programmer -- as well.  
Note that the syntax we use to call a function is based on mathematical notation.  We have all seen something like this:
 &nbsp&nbsp&nbsp  y = sine(x)Here the function we are "running" is the trigonometric sine and the information we are passing in is the argument x.
The function computes a value based on x and produces it.  
The programs that follow will show you examples of the 3 fundamental data types in JavaScript: number, string, and boolean.
All data values in our JavaScript programs will be of these types.  The programs in this module will show you how data values of each type are formed.
We call these individual data values "constants".  A constant is a data value that does not change (i.e., its value is fixed... constant).

Up to now we have asked the user for input and have assumed that the user provides values that correctly match what we want.
However, we cannot in general write programs using this assumption.  
Users make errors. We need to write our programs to deal gracefully with such errors.
At the very minimum we can detect input errors, notify the user, and end execution.  
We might also ask the user to do the input again, correctly and keep asking until the errors end.
As we get more sophisticated we could even try to adapt the input values, correct them and use them in a new form.

type error: the user is asked to input a number but give something like "go heels", which is not a number
format error: the use is asked for an integer, but gives something like 24.713 which is not an integer
range error: the user is asked for a positive integer less than 50, but types in something like -5 or 101.

Write a program that will sum up the elements in an array.  Do it two ways: iteratively (with a loop), and recursively. For each way, print the sum. 
We saw a task earlier (in the overview) that could be done with a loop or with recursion, both giving the same functional results.  
It turns out that any computation that can be done with recursion can be done with looping (and no recursion). Recursion is the functional way to do looping.
This is largely a theoretical consideration, as there are still many times when looping is better to use (more efficient in time and memory use).
In this program we show another example of doing one computation both recursively and non-recursively.
We also illustrate here the use of recursion in manipulating data structures (an array).  
We will write a program that processes an array of numbers two ways.
First in myMain we will declare an array variable and initialize it with these 8 integers:
  var nums = [10,20,30,40,50,60,70,80];
Next we will write an iterative function that will receive an array as a parameter.  It will then sum up
all the elements in the array and return that sum.  The iterative function will get the work done
with a for loop using a pattern we have done several times in other problems.
Next we write a recursive function to do the same computation.  We will pass in an array, and return the sum of the elements in that array.
The base case happens when the array that is passed in has no elements.  We detect this case by looking at the length of the parameter array,
and if that length is 0 we return 0 as the sum (no recursing needed).
If the array has a length or 1 or larger, then the strategy for recursion is to "separate" the array into two pieces: the first element, and the array that
is left when we take the parameter array and take off the first element.  We can call our function recursively on this shortened array, and it will
return the sum of the elements in the parameter array slots 1 on up.  We then add the first element to that and get the sum of the entire array.
Finally write a myMain function that will first call the iterative function on the array, and then call the recursive function on the array.
Print "looping" and then with a second alert, print the sum returned by the iterative function. 
Then print "recursion" and with another alert, print the sum given by the recursive function.
Computer science note.We have said one very important aspect of a recursive function is to make sure that the recursive case is given a smaller problem to work on (and that
the smaller problem is shrinking down to a base case).  In previous examples, the smaller problem meant passing a smaller number as parameter.
Here we are passing a smaller array... an array that is shorter by one element.  We are headed to the base case of a zero-length array.

Write a program that prints the remainder when 26 is divided by 3 (integer division).To do this, we will use the modulo operator (or mod operator) which is expressed with the " % " symbol.  The mod operator can be thought of as the"remainder" operator.  If we do division on numbers in JavaScript we get floating point (or real) arithmetic. With this division, we would expect the expression 
  26 / 3 
to produce the floating point number 8.66666666, or 8 2/3 .  In integer division (not something JavaScript does) we would say the result is 8, with 2 left over.  So what we want for remainder in this problem is the 2 in the numerator of the 2/3 remainder.  "Two left over".
In modular arithmetic (using the mod operator) the evaluation uses integer division and the results are expressed as an integer and a remainder.  Thus we solve this problem this way:
   26 % 3
The mod operator ( % ) is defined this way: a % b is the remainder when a is divided by b, using integer division. 
Here, the integer 3 goes into 26 completely 8 times, with 2 left over.  Therefore, the expression produces the remainder 2. Once
you have programmed the proper code for this problem, try other values to make sure you see how the % operator works.
For example, try these:
  5 % 12   // expect 5
 10 % 5    // expect 0
  5 % 5    // expect 0
 10 % 0    // expect error, divide by 0, Javascript gives Nan for "Not a Number"
 18 % 12   // clock face is mod 12... 18 oclock is really 6 oclock PM
Try some negative numbers as well.
One commonly understood example of modular arithmetic is the common clock face.
As the hands go around over and over, we do not get 13 o'clock, then 25 o'clock, then 37 o'clock, etc as time goes by.
Rather the "time" resets at 12 every revolution.  So instead of 13 o'clock, we get 1 o'clock again.

Write a program that adds 5 to 10, and then multiplies the result by 3. Print out the result as a single number.We have to be careful in this program to pay attention to the order in which the operations are done.  It can affect the final valueof the expression, and can give erroneous results if we are not careful.
You may have learned a memory trick in math class pertaining to order of operation evaluation.  Remember PEMDAS?  These are what we call
operator precedence rules.  The rules tell us which operators must precede which others during evaluation.
The rules are better written P-E-MD-AS I think, as there is no preference for M over D; likewise, no preference for A over S.
According to PEMDAS, when we have an expression to evaluate, we first scan the expression left to right and do all the most deeply nested parentheses first
as sub-expressions.  Then we scan left to right and do exponentiation.  Then we scan left to right and do all multiplication and division as we come to them.
Finally, we scan left to right and do all addition and subtraction, as we come to them.
It pays to know PEMDAS, since JavaScript will evaluate expressions following those rules of operator precedence.  But it also pays in
clarity to use the P part heavily to make sure your expression is evaluated as you intend.  Use parentheses to force the order you want.  Any
readers of your code will appreciate it, and you will make fewer mistakes.

Write a program that searches for occurrences of base pairs in a DNA sequence.  First ask the user to input a DNA sequence (as a string).  Then loop, asking the user for a base pair (as a string of 2 characters) and print the number of times that base pair occurs in the DNA sequence (using the output format below).
Details follow.
 
A DNA sequence representation is a string composed entirely of the capital letter "A", "C", "T", and "G".  For example, each of the following lines represents a DNA sequence:
ACATGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGAGACAGACCCCTAGACACAGAGAGAG
TATGCAGGACAGGGTTTTTGCCCAGGGTGGCAGTATG
AGGATTGAGGTATGGGTATGTTCCCGATTGAGTAGCCAGTATGAGCCAG
AGTTTTTTACAAGTATTTTTCCCAGTAGCCAGAGAGAGAGTCACCCAGT
The following are sample executions:
What DNA sequence? ACATCCTGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGA
What base pair?  CA
The base pair 'CA' occurs 4 times in the DNA sequence 'ACATCCTGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGA'
What base pair? TG
Base pair 'TG' occurs 1 times in DNA sequence 'ACATCCTGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGA'
What base pair? CC
Base pair 'CC' occurs 5 times in DNA sequence 'ACATCCTGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGA'
What base pair? done
Note how we are counting occurrences.  In this string
CCCC
we are saying that "CC" occurs 3 times (not 2).  We do not count the first two characters as a match, and then move on to the 3rd character.  Rather we start with the first "C and notice that there is a "C" following it, for the first match.  We move on to the 2nd character, which is a "C" and we note a "C" following it (for the 2nd match).  We move on to the 3rd character, which is a "C", and we note a "C" following it (for the 3rd match).  I am not sure if this is how biologists count these things, but that is how we will do it here for this program.  We call it a "sliding window"
that is sliding one character at a time.  For fun, you can try
writing your own program where the string "CCCC" would produce 2 matches... a sliding window that slides to the end of any match it finds to keep going.
String functions:There are a couple string functions you may find useful.
First, the function " split " will take a string and produce (return) an array of individual characters, one character from the string stored in each slot location in the array.
A string value in JavaScript is an object, and "split" is a method that can be called on the object.  For example consider this code:
var str = "go heels!";
chars = str.split("");
alert(chars[0]);  // will print "g"
alert(chars[1]);  // will print "o"
alert(chars[2]);  // will print " "  a blank character
alert(chars[3]);  // will print "h"
alert(chars[str.length - 1]);   // will print "!"
Here, using the parameter "" in the call to the split method causes the string to be burst apart into individual characters.  The split method can be used to split strings into
other chunks based on other characters; google it up for more information.
Another possibly useful string method is " charAt ".  This string method will produce (return) a single character, the one found at a specific position in the 
string. Character positions in a string start at 0 and go up to one less than the length of the string.  For example consider this code:
 var bp = "AG" ;
 var first = bp.charAt(0);
 var second = bp.charAt(1);
 var last = bp.charAt(bp.length - 1);
 alert(first);    // prints "A"
 alert(second);  // prints "G"
 alert(last);    // prints "G"
Other challenges: As further practice, you can alter how searching is done and try coding different versions of this program (for practice, not for score).
For example, only count a base pair if it occurs within 10 (or 20, or some limit) characters of some other base pair.  Or dont count a base pair if it immediately follows an 
occurrence of itself.  Or count base pair pairs... if the base pair is AT for example, then look for ATAT and count that.  Make up your own search pattern and code it up.

Write a program that searches for occurrences of base pairs in a DNA sequence.  First ask the user to input a DNA sequence (as a string).  Then loop, asking the user for a base pair (as a string of 2 characters) and print the number of times that base pair occurs in the DNA sequence (using the output format below).
Details follow.
 
A DNA sequence representation is a string composed entirely of the capital letter "A", "C", "T", and "G".  For example, each of the following lines represents a DNA sequence:
ACATGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGAGACAGACCCCTAGACACAGAGAGAG
TATGCAGGACAGGGTTTTTGCCCAGGGTGGCAGTATG
AGGATTGAGGTATGGGTATGTTCCCGATTGAGTAGCCAGTATGAGCCAG
AGTTTTTTACAAGTATTTTTCCCAGTAGCCAGAGAGAGAGTCACCCAGT
The following are sample executions:
What DNA sequence? ACATCCTGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGA
What base pair?  CA
The base pair 'CA' occurs 4 times in the DNA sequence 'ACATCCTGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGA'
What base pair? TG
Base pair 'TG' occurs 1 times in DNA sequence 'ACATCCTGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGA'
What base pair? CC
Base pair 'CC' occurs 5 times in DNA sequence 'ACATCCTGAGACAGACAGACCCCCAGA'
What base pair? done
Note how we are counting occurrences.  In this string
CCCC
we are saying that "CC" occurs 3 times (not 2).  We do not count the first two characters as a match, and then move on to the 3rd character.  Rather we start with the first "C and notice that there is a "C" following it, for the first match.  We move on to the 2nd character, which is a "C" and we note a "C" following it (for the 2nd match).  We move on to the 3rd character, which is a "C", and we note a "C" following it (for the 3rd match).  I am not sure if this is how biologists count these things, but that is how we will do it here for this program.  We call it a "sliding window"
that is sliding one character at a time.  For fun, you can try
writing your own program where the string "CCCC" would produce 2 matches... a sliding window that slides to the end of any match it finds to keep going.
String functions:There are a couple string functions you may find useful.
First, the function " split " will take a string and produce (return) an array of individual characters, one character from the string stored in each slot location in the array.
A string value in JavaScript is an object, and "split" is a method that can be called on the object.  For example consider this code:
var str = "go heels!";
chars = str.split("");
alert(chars[0]);  // will print "g"
alert(chars[1]);  // will print "o"
alert(chars[2]);  // will print " "  a blank character
alert(chars[3]);  // will print "h"
alert(chars[str.length - 1]);   // will print "!"
Here, using the parameter "" in the call to the split method causes the string to be burst apart into individual characters.  The split method can be used to split strings into
other chunks based on other characters; google it up for more information.
Another possibly useful string method is " charAt ".  This string method will produce (return) a single character, the one found at a specific position in the 
string. Character positions in a string start at 0 and go up to one less than the length of the string.  For example consider this code:
 var bp = "AG" ;
 var first = bp.charAt(0);
 var second = bp.charAt(1);
 var last = bp.charAt(bp.length - 1);
 alert(first);    // prints "A"
 alert(second);  // prints "G"
 alert(last);    // prints "G"

Methods: Functions inside objects 
Objects are the capstone item in the list of the Great 8 concepts we find in all object-oriented programming languages.
Up to now, we have seen that an object is a way of binding data values ("fields") together so that they remain
associated for a common purpose... such as representing different pieces of information about a person
(name, age, address, pay rate, hours worked, etc.).
Now we will see that functions can also be fields in an object.   We call a function inside an object a "method" of that object.
Thus, an object binds together data fields, and functions (methods)
that operate on those data fields.  This makes an object an abstraction of a program in general.
We can think of our "programs" as collections of objects that call each others' methods in order to get work done.
The methods inside an object will allow us to think of an object as being able to do work for us.
In previous programs, we had an object constructor "makePersonObject" that would create an object that
represented a worker at a company.  The object had a field that told how many hours that person worked, and a field that
told the pay rate the person earned per hour. To compute the amount of pay the person earned, we directly accessed the hours field and the payrate field in 
the object, retrieved their values, and multiplied those values together.  We did this in the problem "Construct person object"   in module "Basic Objects" if you would like
to refer back to the code.
Now, we will be able to add a method (function) to the person object so that the person object can do that computation internally, where the hours and payrate fields are kept 
(we will do this in one of the following problems).  We can then
have a person object do that work for us, and simply report the total pay in response to our code elsewhere calling a function (a method) in the object.
In essence, we will contact the object and get it to do what we were doing in our code before, but now we do not have to remember the details
of what the internal data fields are named.  We let the object worry about that in the "pay" function, and we simple call that function and wait for the results.
We will not look inside the object at its data fields.  The syntax for this will be:
  var persObj = makePersonObject();
  var totalPay = personObj.pay();
To do this, we will alter the  "makePersonObject"  constructor to add the method to each objects it creates.  Let's name that method "pay".  
This method takes no arguments, and when called, it returns the total
pay earned by the person the object represents.  
This is computed by multiplying the person's pay rate by the person's hours worked.
To get credit for this overview:Let's take the "makePersonObject" code we had before and alter to put a very simple function into each object it makes.
This function will report back the name of the person when it is called. Here is the new constructor code (and a myMain to exercise the constructor):
"use strict";

function myMain () {
  var emp = makePersonObject();  // this makes a person object "emp"
  alert( emp.getName() ); // this is a method call on the object "emp"
}

function makePersonObject ( ) {
  var perObj = {
    id: Number(prompt("person ID number?")),
    name: prompt("person name?"),
    hours: Number(prompt("hours worked?")),
    payrate: Number(prompt("pay rate?")),

    // this is how we put a function into an object
    // we make an anonymous function and bind it to a field name
    getName: function ( ) { return this.name; } 

  };
  return perObj;
}

myMain();
Here we create a person object in myMain, and then call the "getName" in that object. We then print out the string returned by that method.  In this way, the
object is "telling us" the name it contains.
Put this code in your editor window, test it locally, and then submit it for score.
Software Engineering lesson.Not looking inside an object at its data fields... letting the object itself worry about manipulating the data fields... getting information from an
object by calling methods and letting the object send us data... this is called "information hiding".  We think of an object as being a
"black box" and we don't see it internals.  We do see it's public interface... it's methods and how to call them (the arguments the methods need when called).
If we want information, we ask the object to supply it rather that reaching inside and taking it.  In this way, complicated manipulations can be written once
and put into the object as methods.  This is an example of the DRY principle at work. We do not repeat complicated manipulations of object data fields all
over our code; rather we put them into the objects, as methods, each defined once.  Then we call the functions when we need the information,
Some programming disciplines go as far as making data field invisible.. unable to be read outside the object.  Then to get something simple 
(like the value of the name field in our person object) we would put a method like "getName()" in the person object.  Maybe we put in a "setName(s)" method 
as well, in case we need to change the name stored in the object.  We would not be allowed to do something direct like persObj.name = "Smith" from outside the
object.  Information hiding helps keep the data in the object consistent, since it cannot be changed by any code that it not a methods in the object.
These simple methods that produce, or update, the values of the data fields are called "getters" and "setters".  The "getName()" methods we wrote in this overview code
is an example of a "getter" method.

The instructional point is to make clear the reason to use the "this" reference in an object,
as well as to clarify the distinctions between a method (function) and a data field.  The "this" object reference gives dynamic capabilities,
allowing an object to compute information from what happens to be stored in the object fields at the time of method call.  Referencing
variables and parameters in the object constructor when the object is made will capture values that are static... maintain the values
that existed at the time of object creation and will not change dynamically.
The code changes we need to make are detailed, so just follow along in order
In function makePersonObject let's now make a few more changes.  First, rename the "pay" function to be called "payFunc".
Let's also add a new field called "payData" that simple takes the hours and payrate parameters and multiplies them (not using the "this"
object reference).

Then alert a call to the payFunc method.  Run the program and see that both outputs are the same.
Now, after those alerts in myMain, add a line that doubles the hours field in the person object ( something like emp.hours *= 2; ).  We have just doubled the hours
that person worked, and we should see a doubling in the total pay.  Repeat the two different alerts and see what happens.
The reason we now see a difference is because the payFunc method computes using whatever happens to be stored in the rate and hours fields at the time the
method is called (the "this" keyword says to use the fields dynamically).  
So if we change the values stored in those fields during computation, the result returned by the methods call will change accordingly.
However, the payData field is static; it's value is created and stored when the object is made, using values from local variables (parameters) in the constructor memory map.
Those values are fixed at construction time and do not change as computation progresses.
